"# Chapter 1 — Records

A record is a named cluster of values. You name the type, you name the
fields, and Scheme gives you a constructor, a type predicate, and one
accessor per field. That is it. Records are the R7RS answer to what
other languages call a struct or a data class.

`define-record-type` is the whole verb. One form defines the type,
the constructor, the predicate, and the accessors together, so the
shape sits in one place where anyone reading the code can see it.

## Why records exist

Two reasons. First, they give names to slots. Reaching for the third
element of a list works until you swap positions two and three, at
which point every caller reads the wrong thing. Records give you
`(point-y p)` instead of `(third p)` — the name stays put even if
the slot order changes.

Second, they give you a distinct type. A list holding an x and a y is
still just a list. A record holding the same two numbers is a
`point`, and `(point? p)` is `#t` for that value and `#f` for
anything else.

## Problem 1 — Say who this is

Define a record for a person with a name and an age. Build one.
Read the fields back out.

```
(define-record-type person
  (make-person name age)
  person?
  (name person-name)
  (age person-age))

(define alice (make-person \"Alice\" 30))
(display (person-name alice))
(display \" is \")
(display (person-age alice))
(display \" years old.\")
;; => Alice is 30 years old.
```

Read the shape. `define-record-type` takes:

- **The type name** — `person`.
- **The constructor spec** — `(make-person name age)`. This declares a
  procedure named `make-person` that takes two arguments and returns a
  fresh `person`.
- **The predicate** — `person?`. Given any value, returns `#t` if the
  value is a person and `#f` otherwise.
- **The field specs** — `(name person-name)` and `(age person-age)`.
  Each declares a field name plus an accessor procedure.

Once defined, `person?` reliably distinguishes a person from anything
else. That is the type discipline records buy you.

## Problem 2 — A record with an update

Records are immutable by default. If you want to change a field, you
build a new record with the new value. But `define-record-type` will
also generate a MUTATOR if you name one:

```
(define-record-type counter
  (make-counter n)
  counter?
  (n counter-n set-counter-n!))

(define c (make-counter 0))
(set-counter-n! c 5)
(display (counter-n c))
;; => 5
```

The fourth item in the field spec — `set-counter-n!` — is the mutator.
It exists only because we named it. Leave it out and the field is
read-only.

## Problem 3 — A predicate that discriminates two record types

Records are more useful than lists when your program has two kinds of
thing that shouldn't be confused. Let's give it a shape it can't
mix up.

```
(define-record-type circle
  (make-circle radius)
  circle?
  (radius circle-radius))

(define-record-type square
  (make-square side)
  square?
  (side square-side))

(define (area shape)
  (cond ((circle? shape) (* 3.14159 (circle-radius shape) (circle-radius shape)))
        ((square? shape) (* (square-side shape) (square-side shape)))
        (else 'unknown-shape)))

(display (area (make-circle 5)))
;; => 78.53975
(display (area (make-square 4)))
;; => 16
```

Notice that `circle?` and `square?` don't get confused. A `circle` is
NOT a `square`. `(circle? (make-square 3))` is `#f`. That is what a
type is for.

## Problem 4 (expert) — Records inside a list, filtered by predicate

Once you have records, you compose them with the higher-order verbs
you already know: `map`, `filter`, `fold`.

```
(define-record-type book
  (make-book title pages)
  book?
  (title book-title)
  (pages book-pages))

(define library
  (list (make-book \"The Little Schemer\" 210)
        (make-book \"SICP\" 883)
        (make-book \"Motoi Notebook\" 60)))

(define short-books
  (filter (lambda (b) (< (book-pages b) 300)) library))

(for-each (lambda (b)
            (display (book-title b))
            (display \"\\n\"))
          short-books)
;; => The Little Schemer
;;    Motoi Notebook
```

The record shape composes cleanly with `filter` because we can pass
the accessor as a projection: `(book-pages b)` returns the number,
`<` compares, `filter` keeps the ones that pass.

## Capstone — A state machine as records

Motoi's world-loop wants a state value on every tick. Records give
that state a shape you can read.

```
(define-record-type game-state
  (make-game-state score lives paused?)
  game-state?
  (score game-state-score)
  (lives game-state-lives)
  (paused? game-state-paused?))

(define initial (make-game-state 0 3 #f))

(define (score-up s)
  (make-game-state (+ (game-state-score s) 10)
                   (game-state-lives s)
                   (game-state-paused? s)))

(define after-one-hit (score-up initial))
(display (game-state-score after-one-hit))
;; => 10
```

`score-up` is a pure function: given a state, it returns a new state.
Nothing was mutated. That is the shape of a functional program with
records — the record is the tuple, the update-function is the
transition, and time is the fold of transitions over the initial
state.

## What's next

In Chapter 2 we get exceptions. Records tell us what a value is;
exceptions tell us what went wrong. Together they give programs
enough shape to say clearly what happened and why.
")
